zRAM is this model quantisation?

No—zRAM and model quantisation are completely different things. They both save memory, but at totally different layers.
Let’s separate them cleanly so you don’t mix them up 👇

🧠 zRAM (system-level memory trick)
zRAM = compressed RAM managed by the OS
Used in:

Linux
What it does:
Takes your existing RAM
Compresses what’s stored in it
Lets you fit more data into the same physical memory
👉 Think: “make RAM more efficient”
Example:
16GB RAM → behaves like ~24–32GB (depending on compression)
Key point:
Works on everything in memory (apps, OS, models, etc.)
Does NOT change your AI model itself
⚙️ Quantisation (model-level optimization)
Used in tools like:
llama.cpp
What it does:
Shrinks the actual AI model file
Reduces precision of numbers (weights)
👉 Think: “make the model smaller”
Example:
13B model:
FP16 → ~26GB
Q4 → ~6–8GB
Key point:
Happens before loading into RAM
Directly reduces memory usage + speeds up inference
🔥 The difference (simple)
Concept	zRAM 🧠	Quantisation ⚙️
Layer	OS / system	Model / AI
Changes model?	❌ No	✅ Yes
How it saves memory	Compression in RAM	Smaller model file
Speed impact	Slight overhead	Usually faster
Use case	General memory boost	Run bigger models
🧩 How they work together (this is the power move)
For your airgapped AI system:
Quantisation
→ makes model small enough to run
zRAM
→ helps fit everything in memory smoothly
mmap (via llama.cpp)
→ streams model from disk if needed
👉 Combined = massive effective memory expansion
🧾 Bottom line
❌ zRAM is NOT quantisation
✅ zRAM = compresses RAM
✅ Quantisation = compresses the model
