can't you compress it instead

You can compress things—but the key is what exactly you’re compressing, because that determines whether it actually helps or just slows everything down.
Short answer:
👉 Yes, but you should compress the model, not rely on compressing RAM.

Let’s break it properly.

🧠 1. Compressing RAM (zRAM) — what you’re thinking of
This is:
zRAM
What happens:
Data in memory gets compressed on the fly
Why it’s limited:
CPU has to compress/decompress constantly
LLM workloads are already heavy
Can introduce latency
👉 So yes—you are compressing it…
…but it’s a backup efficiency layer, not your main solution.
⚙️ 2. Compressing the model (THIS is what you want)
Using:
llama.cpp
This is called:
Quantisation
You are literally:
Compressing weights
Reducing precision
Making the model smaller before it even hits RAM
🔥 Why this works better
Instead of:
“Let’s squeeze a huge model into RAM”
You do:
“Let’s make the model smaller so it fits naturally”
Real example:
A model like 13B:
Raw → ~26GB
Q8 → ~13GB
Q4 → ~6–8GB
Q2 → ~4GB
👉 That’s real compression with performance gains
🧩 3. There is another type of compression (rarely used)
You could:
Compress model files (zip, etc.)
Decompress on load
But:
Adds load time
No runtime benefit
Not used in serious inference setups
🧠 4. What advanced setups actually do
For a high-performance airgapped system (like yours), the stack is:
✅ Step 1 — Quantise model (PRIMARY compression)
→ biggest impact
✅ Step 2 — Use mmap
→ stream model from disk
✅ Step 3 — Add zRAM
→ smooth out memory pressure
🔥 The truth (important)
If you try to rely on “just compressing it” (RAM-level thinking):
❌ You hit CPU bottlenecks
❌ Performance becomes unstable
❌ Agents slow down or stall
If you compress at the model level:
✅ Stable
✅ Fast
✅ Scalable
🧾 Clean mental model
Quantisation = shrink the AI brain
zRAM = pack your desk tighter
mmap = grab papers only when needed
